# Agent Conventions

Before architectural or cross-cutting changes, read the project's agent docs:

1. `.agents/AGENTS.md` (primary)
2. `claude.md` at repo root, if present
3. `agents.md` at repo root, if present

Also scan `.agents/` for any additional convention files. Use those docs for bounded-context ownership, import boundaries, terrain/foot sync, security, and performance pitfalls. Do not restate them here — read the source files.

## Performance — first-class requirement

ClaudeCitizen is a **real-time web game** (React UI + Three.js/WebGL) targeting smooth play on consumer hardware, with a future **Nest.js MMO backend** (WebSockets, authoritative simulation). Performance is not a polish pass — it is a **core product constraint**. A Star Citizen–scale world on the web fails instantly if the main thread stalls, draw calls explode, or sync work scales with player count.

**Treat every change as a frame-budget decision.** Aim for sustained interactive framerate; profile when unsure; prefer bounded, incremental work over "do it all now" loops.

### When performance matters (always)

- Game loop, render path, terrain/LOD, vegetation, ship/station loading
- React UI that re-renders during play (HUD, menus, editor panels)
- Per-frame or per-tick simulation (`world/`, `flight/`, `player/`)
- Asset size, mesh complexity, texture resolution, GLB/GLTF loads
- Workers, caching, and anything that can block the main thread
- Future server: tick rate, broadcast fan-out, payload size, DB hot paths

### Client — React + Three.js

- **Main thread is sacred.** Heavy work belongs in Web Workers (`planet_tile_worker.js`), async loads, or spread across frames — never unbounded sync loops on the hot path.
- **Respect existing budgets.** Per-frame tile/vegetation build caps, LOD selection, and quality presets (`?quality=performance|balanced|high`) exist because unbounded work freezes the game at 0 FPS.
- **React stays out of the render loop.** UI updates on state/events; do not drive Three.js from React render churn. Memoize; avoid new object/array allocations every frame in shared paths.
- **Three.js discipline.** Reuse geometries/materials; instancing where possible; frustum/distance culling; minimize scene graph churn and `dispose()` leaks.
- **Measure.** Use the in-game FPS counter and quality presets when validating changes; see AGENTS.md "Terrain mesh vs foot placement" for terrain-specific traps.

### Server — Nest.js / MMO (future)

- **Server tick is a budget too.** Simulation, interest management, and broadcasts must scale with concurrent players — design for O(players-in-range), not O(world).
- **WebSockets: small, frequent beats.** Prefer compact binary or minimal JSON deltas; batch when it helps; never ship full world state every tick.
- **Authority without blocking.** Nest handlers stay thin; heavy domain work in services; no synchronous DB/network chains on the hot path.
- **Client sends intents, server decides outcomes** — keeps cheating down and avoids duplicating expensive simulation on every client.

## When to read

- Adding features or changing module boundaries
- Touching terrain mesh, foot placement, or LOD
- Working with assets, builds, secrets, or protected paths
- Any change that affects architecture or cross-layer dependencies
- Anything on the main thread, in the frame loop, or on a future realtime server path

## Quick triggers

- New feature → which bounded context owns it? (`world/`, `flight/`, `player/`, `render/`)
- Terrain / character grounding → see AGENTS.md "Terrain mesh vs foot placement"
- Assets / build / secrets → see AGENTS.md "Security"
- Editor / prefab / GLB node operations → `.cursor/rules/prefab-editor.mdc` and AGENTS.md "Editor (dev-only)"
- Slow or stuttery? → check frame budgets, LOD, React re-renders, and sync work before adding features

## Key reminders

- Domain logic lives in `world/`, `flight/`, `player/` — not in `render/` or `app.js`
- Foot placement uses `sampleFootPlanetSurface()` / `getFootSurfaceSampleLevel()`, not always max LOD
- Never commit or relocate `protected/` assets
- No unit tests in this project
- User owns QA. Do not run tests, browser QA, screenshot checks, dev-server validation, `npm run build`, `npm run typecheck`, or `npm run lint` unless explicitly asked for validation. At the end of a multi-file feature or spike, run `npm run lint` and fix errors (and trivial warnings in touched files when practical). If validation is skipped, say so in the handoff. For explicit commit requests, run `npm run typecheck` and `npm run lint` first unless told not to.
- **Prisma:** Agents may run `npm run prisma:generate`, `npm run prisma:migrate`, and `npm run prisma:deploy` when schema/migrations change (Alan has authorized migrate). Prefer `prisma:deploy` when the migration SQL already exists; use `prisma:migrate -- --name <slug>` when creating a new migration so the CLI does not hang on interactive prompts.
- Do not start dev servers. Vite and API servers are normally already running locally. Do not run `npm run dev`, `npm run dev:server`, `npm run start:dev`, `vite`, `tsx watch`, or similar long-running local servers unless explicitly asked. If server context is needed, check existing ports/processes or ask first.
- **If it can freeze the tab or tank server tick rate, fix or bound it before shipping**
